{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure commonly appears at the live boundary between embedding provider output and index schema (e.g., model/version dimension drift). A stubbed embedding client can hide this. This is not Agentic because the behavior checks vector shape, not model judgment quality. Workflow is disqualified by behavior text: it validates a single embedding output contract, not a multi-step agent chain.","test_description":"Call the real embedding endpoint configured for production-like model/version, then attempt insert/search against a real test index configured to the expected dimension; assert exact dimension match and that mismatches fail fast with a clear error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The similarity search returns results ordered by descending cosine similarity score.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is module handoff: query vector -> vector-store retrieval -> API ranking/serialization. This is beyond a single function, but does not inherently require real network/OS/subprocess. System was considered and rejected because behavior text only requires score ordering semantics, which can be reproduced with an in-process/local test vector store fixture.","test_description":"Seed a local test vector index with fixed vectors and known cosine scores to a test query, run search through service + repository layers, and assert returned scores are monotonic non-increasing and item order matches expected ranking.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of at least some results compared to the raw similarity ranking when the query has nuanced intent.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM contextual judgment for nuanced intent; deterministic stubs will always pass and can miss real ranking-quality failures. Workflow was considered and rejected because this behavior targets one model decision step (re-rank), not correctness across multiple agentic steps chained together.","test_description":"Use a fixed query/result-set fixture with known nuanced intent cases, call the real re-ranking model, and assert at least one pairwise inversion vs raw similarity ranking in a statistically robust run policy (e.g., pass threshold over repeated trials).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A query with no close matches in the database returns an empty result set rather than low-relevance noise.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is integration of similarity thresholding/filter logic with search results. It can be caught with controlled vectors and threshold config in local modules. System was considered and rejected: real network/OS behavior is not required by the behavior text. Agentic was considered and rejected: behavior is about threshold policy for 'no close matches,' not model quality judgment.","test_description":"Create a test index where all candidate vectors are below configured similarity threshold for the query vector, execute search via API service stack, and assert response contains zero items (not truncated noise).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.69,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Latency SLO is a real-infrastructure property (network hops, live model/database latency, serialization, runtime overhead). In-process mocks hide true tail/median timing. Agentic was considered and rejected because pass/fail is time-based, not output-quality-based. Workflow was considered and rejected because this behavior does not validate multi-step agentic correctness, only end-to-end performance.","test_description":"Run production-like end-to-end load test against deployed service with real embedding/vector DB/LLM dependencies, collect latency distribution for representative query mix, and assert p50 < 2.0s over a stable sample window.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.79,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.09}}]}
